%[text] %[text:anchor:H_8083] ## Ideal Model:
%[text] ![Coupled_Pendulum_diagram.drawio.png](text:image:282f)
%[text] Upon staring at your real world model for long enough you may eventually find the the proper parameters to extract in order to turn your problem into math. Here we have identified the characteristic parameters or, if you will, eigen-parameters, to be:
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\vec{u\_i}(t) := \\text{ displacement from equilibrium } \\\\ \n\\theta\_i(t) := \\text{ angle from equlibrium }\\\\\nr\_i := \\text{ length of i'th pendulum} \\\\\nm\_i := \\text{ mass oif the i'th pendulum  } \\\\\nk := \\text{ spring constant } $
%[text]{"align":"center"} 
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\left\[ \\begin{array}{ c }\n\n\\ddot{u}\_1 \\\\\n\\ddot{u}\_2\n\n\\end{array} \\right\] = \\left\[ \\begin{array}{l}\n\n \\frac{g}{r} + \\frac{k}{m} &  -\\frac{k}{m}\\\\\n-\\frac{k}{m}                    & \\frac{g}{r} + \\frac{k}{m}\n\n\\end{array} \\right\]  \\left\[ \\begin{array}{c}\n\nu\_1 \\\\\nu\_2\n\n\n\\end{array} \\right\] $
clear; close; clc;

g = 9.81;
r = 1.75;
k = 6.528; 
m = 3.336; %% should be 3.336

%[text] Main Diagonal:
a = g/r + k/m;
%[text] Super Diagonal:
b = -k/m;
%[text] Sub Diagonal:
c = -k/m;
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_208a] ## Tridiagonal Toeplitz Matricies:
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\left\[ \\begin{array}{ c } \n\na & b &           &   \\\\ \nc & a & b        &  \\\\\n   & c & \\ddots & \\ddots & \\\\\n   &    &\\ddots & \\ddots  & b\\\\\n   &    &           & c          & a\n\n\\end{array} \\right\]${"altText":"tri-diagonal Toeplitz Matrix"}
%[text]{"align":"center"} $ a=\\frac{g}{r}+\\frac{k}{m} ,\\ b = -\\frac{k}{m} \\ \\& \\ c = -\\frac{k}{m}$
%[text]{"align":"center"} 
%[text]{"align":"center"} 
%[text] 
%[text] EigenValues and EigenVectors:
Eigen_Values = sqrt( -a + 2.*( sqrt(b*c) ).*cospi( (1:2) ./ (2 + 1) ) );

Eigen_Vectors = sinpi( ((1:2).*(1:2)')./ (2+1) );

SOLVE( 1:0.1:2, [1,1], [-1,1], a, b, c, 2 );


function U = SOLVE( varargin )
    %persistent == static
    persistent Eigen_Vectors Eigen_Values;

    tspan = varargin{1};
    u_i = varargin{2};
    v_i = varargin{3};

    % ( tspan, u_i, v_i, a, b, c ) 
    if( nargin == 7 )

        a = varargin{4};
        b = varargin{5};
        c = varargin{6};
        n = varargin{7};
        Eigen_Vectors = sinpi( ((1:n).*(1:n)')./ (n+1) );
        Eigen_Values = sqrt( -a + 2.*( sqrt(b*c) ).*cospi( (1:n) ./ (n + 1) ) );

    end

    C = mldivide(Eigen_Vectors , u_i');
    C = C - mldivide( Eigen_Vectors.*Eigen_Values , v_i' );

    U = real( Eigen_Vectors * ( C .* exp( (Eigen_Values' .* tspan ) ) ) );

end
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_0360] ### 
%[text] 
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_1bc7] ## Real world data:
%[text] 
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_9ba0] ### Analysis tools
% this function, takes in a file name and a time span and returns a data
% strcture containing: 
% U1, U2      : displacments of each mass
% V1, V2      : velocities of each mass( only if data file contains velocities )
% t           : time range
% freq        : aprox frequency of mass 1 from a fourier curve fit
% Modeled     : Modeled displacments of each mass based on the intial values of the data
function DATA = Extract( filename, tspan )

    Temp = importdata( filename ).data;
    span = ( find( Temp(:,1)==tspan(1) ):find( Temp(:,1)==tspan(2) ) );

    if numel( Temp(1,:) ) == 5
        index_2 = 4;
        DATA.V1 = Temp( span, 3 );
        DATA.V2 = Temp( span, 5 );
    else
        index_2 = 3;
    end
    
    
    DATA.U1 = Temp( span, 2 );
    DATA.U1 = DATA.U1 - mean( DATA.U1 );

    DATA.U2 = Temp( span, index_2 );
    DATA.U2 = DATA.U2 - mean( DATA.U2 );

    DATA.t = Temp( span, 1 ) - tspan(1);


    DATA.freq = fit( DATA.t, DATA.U1, "fourier1" ).w;

    if( numel(Temp(1,:)) == 5 )
        DATA.Modeled = SOLVE( DATA.t', [DATA.U1(1),DATA.U2(1)],[DATA.V1(2),DATA.V2(2)] );
    else
        DATA.Modeled = SOLVE( DATA.t', [DATA.U1(2),DATA.U2(2)],[0,0] );
    end

end

%    It's in the name, this function makes a plot formated for the above data
%    structure
function PlotData( Data, Trial )

    scatter( Data.t, [ Data.U1,Data.U2 ], 20, '.' );
    hold on
    plot( Data.t, Data.Modeled );
    hold off
    title(Trial);
    legend( ["Mass A","Mass B","Mass A Modeled","Mass B Modeled"] );


end
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_90aa] ### 
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_3d11] ### Trial set up:
%[text]     In general it seems like there are two ways to approach this:
%[text] 1. Set up a trial for specific initial conditions
%[text] 2. Set up up trial for a specific behavior \
%[text]         The first method would make it easy to set up the model (assuming your initial conditions are precise enough), but this method adds extra variables to pay attention to. while the second method is laser focused on the important characteristic (the eigenvectors), and since that is the thing we are intent on validating it seems prudent to focus on that. So, I think well go that route, and we'll need different set ups to test each mode:
%[text] 
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_8f67] #### Normal Mode 1:
%[text] Goal: Displace both masses an equal amount
%[text] 1. Jeff's ruler method: essentially make a parallelogram out of the two pendulums, and a ruler. if you make this parallelogram when the two masses are at equilibrium, then (ideally) if you shear this parallelogram, by moving the ruler and the masses to the side, the equilibrium should be preserved. The only problem with this is that we don't live in an ideal world and you will probably introduce some extenuates movement when you release the masses. ALSO if you grab the masses from the side, they will try to twist when you shear the parallelogram  \
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_183e] #### Normal Mode 2:
%[text] Goal: Displace both masses an equal and opposite amount
%[text] 
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_4a09] #### Mixed Mode:
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_8218] ### 
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_2ffd] 
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_4306] ### Normal Mode 1:
%[text] 
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_151d] #### Trial 1:
Mode_1_Trial_1 = Extract( "Normal_Mode_1_full.txt",[57.267,77.367] );
PlotData( Mode_1_Trial_1,"Trial 1" ); %[output:02b8dabe]
( Mode_1_Trial_1.freq - imag(Eigen_Values(1)) ) / imag(Eigen_Values(1)) * 100 %[output:4adcf9f7]
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_13e7] ####     Jitter:
%[text]         There seems to be a consistent jitter in the data around 4 - 6 seconds into the replay. I think this is independent of the recording time, since the clips were chopped up after the fact, so it could be from post processing:
%[text] 1.     Clipmaster: the jitter could be introduced by the goofy editing software used to chop up the clips
%[text] 2.     Tracker: the jitter could be from a poor autotrack in the tracker software( the jitter does seem to be caused by two data points essentially on top of each other ) \
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_5fc7] ####     Non ideal pendulum behavior:
%[text]         One of my colleges noticed that the real world model we're testing on doesn't necessarily act as an ideal pendulum. Our approximation of a pendulum is a actually a square platform suspended from each corner by a wire that is anchored to a utility rack. These wires are splayed out on the axis perpendicular to the direction of travel and evenly spaced on the axis parallel to the direction of travel. In theory this should create a parallel linkage whose center of mass follows the trajectory of an ideal pendulum (a perfectly circular path). Even though, in practice, there really is no such thing as a perfect circle, we can assume that the slight differences will be negligible compared to the other sources of error in this system ( measurements of the coeffs, and displacement, etc ). However, that assumption gets worse and worse the further our linkage strays from an ideal parallelogram. The question is, How much worse does this assumption get over the range of realistic values( keeping in mind our previous assumption of small angles )
%[text]{"align":"center"} 
%[text]     Change: distance between the wires
%[text]     effect: change in period
%[text]     Cause:
%[text] 1.  Mass no longer follows an ideal circular path and cant be modeled as a pendulum. - after staring at a [desmos](https://www.desmos.com/calculator/uangxzzjif) graph for long enough it doesn't seem like the path deviates from our ideal circular path by any appreciable amount( at least while staying within the limits of our small angle approximation ).
%[text] 2.  **Moments introduced by the platform sway take up some of the potential energy leading to a lower acceleration due to the pendulum ( lower return force means longer period )**
%[text] 3.  *The true radius of the pendulum changed* - This doesn't line up since the radius decreases and this should cause an increase in frequency, but the observed change is a decrease in frequency \
%[text]{"align":"center"} ![Non-ideal_Pendulum_diagram.drawio.png](text:image:731c)
%[text]     Either way, let's just try our best to make the our real world model look like the diagram on the left, and if that lines up with our theory we can move on.
%[text] 
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_781f] #### Trial 2:
%[text]     Changes:
%[text] - Payed extra attention to the spacing of the wires at the top of the rig. They should be spaced approx 11.8 cm apart. \
Mode_1_Trial_2 = Extract( "Normal_Mode_1_2.txt", [0,63.8] );
PlotData( Mode_1_Trial_2, "Normal Mode 1 Trial 2" ); %[output:1be11acc]
( Mode_1_Trial_2.freq - imag(Eigen_Values(1)) ) / imag(Eigen_Values(1)) * 100 %[output:3cb3022d]
%[text] 
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_97c8] ### Normal Mode 2:
%[text] 
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_03ef] ### Trial 1:
Mode_2_Trial_1 = Extract( "Ian_Moss_Normal_Mode_2.txt", [1.6,31.1] );
PlotData( Mode_2_Trial_1,"Mode 2 Trial 1" ); %[output:85d1940d]
( Mode_2_Trial_1.freq - imag(Eigen_Values(2)) ) / imag(Eigen_Values(2)) * 100 %[output:7a25b814]
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_93e4] ### Trial 2:
%[text] Changes:
%[text] - Payed extra attention to the spacing of the wires at the top of the rig. They should be spaced approx 11.8 cm apart. \
Mode_2_Trial_2 = Extract( "Mode_2_Trial_2.1.txt", [0,29.967] );
PlotData( Mode_2_Trial_2,"Mode 2 Trial 2" ); %[output:968b765f]
( Mode_2_Trial_2.freq - imag(Eigen_Values(2)) ) / imag(Eigen_Values(2)) * 100 %[output:82b15c0e]
%[text] Trial 2 has  a slightly better error, but it's still off by a considerable amount, maybe the pendulum legs still aren't quite parallel causing the g/l affect on the frequency to be inaccurate. however it seems that by changing the mass to 3.8 we can get down to a reasonable error, so this may be caused by some new error in the k/m term.
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_1922] ### Trial 3:
%[text]     Changes:
%[text] - placed the ruler between the two bolt threads on the bottom of each platform. \
Mode_2_Trial_3 = Extract( "Mode_2_Trial_3.txt",[0,31.467] );
PlotData( Mode_2_Trial_3, "Mode 2 Trial 3" ); %[output:92b034ff]
( Mode_2_Trial_3.freq - imag(Eigen_Values(2)) ) / imag(Eigen_Values(2)) * 100 %[output:9429f1d8]
%[text] 
