%[text] %[text:anchor:H_87f6] ## Side Quest's
%[text] 
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_778d] ### Calculating pi with a pendulum:
%[text]     Seeing as it's pi day and we have all this real world data from pendulums that we just found the complex frequencies of, I don't see why we shouldn't make a horrible approximation for pi.
%[text] 
%[text] For any given complex exponential function, the period and frequency can be related by:
%[text] 
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\n\n\n\n \\ \\ \\ e^{0i} = 1 = e^{2\\pi i} \\ \\\\  \\Rightarrow   e^{  0 \\omega i } = 1 = e^{ \\left(\\frac{2\\pi}{\\omega} \\right) \\omega i }   \\\\ \n \\Rightarrow \\ T\\omega=2\\pi \\\\ \\Rightarrow \\pi=\\frac{T\\omega}{2}\n\n$
%[text] Note: this relationship is a result of the math we are using to model the system, the general relationship between frequency and period is simply:
%[text]{"align":"center"} $Tf =1$
%[text] It just happens to be that the the base period of a complex exponential function (which traces a unit circle in the complex plane) is 2pi. This is an important distinction because if we tried to calculate pi by experimental measuring both the period and frequency of a real world pendulum, well, you would end up with a very very bad approximation.
%[text] 
%[text] So, in order to calculate pie all we need is an experimental value for the period of our pendulum. We can achieve this by just counting the oscillations over a time interval and then dividing the number of oscillations observed by the length of the interval. We'll use Trial 2 for Mode 1 because that is the most accurate trial so far:
period = Mode_1_Trial_2.t( numel( Mode_1_Trial_2.t ) ) / 24 %[output:448d0982]

angular_frequency = sqrt( g/r ) %[output:96d36435]

my_pi = angular_frequency * period / 2 %[output:64db7fdb]
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_8908] ## Important considerations:
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_1ffb] ### Equilibrium: 
%[text]     Since we define our model with respect to a displacement from the equilibrium, to be able to use this model we need a usable definition of the equilibrium. 
%[text] possible solutions:
%[text] 1.     Record a few seconds of the masses at rest before displacing them. This would become quite cumbersome to set up, since getting a good run is essentially trial and error. ( A lot of stopping and re-setting )
%[text] 2.     Mark the equilibrium on the background white board, to be extracted using tracker software at any time. this assumes that the equilibrium doesn't change(it really shouldn't), may also introduce extra parallax error.
%[text] 3.  <u>**Or, you just take the average value over multiple FULL periods, and call that the equalibrium.**</u> \
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_3d02] ### 
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_25bb] ### Damping:
%[text]     In our idealized model we neglected to account for drag, assuming that drag effects would be negligible, so in order to make that assumption appropriate we need to minimize the effects drag might have on the system.
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_574d] ####         Sources:
%[text] -     air resistance ( can't realistically be minimized and also definitely has little effect )
%[text] -     Thermal losses in the spring ( probably minuscule aswell )
%[text] -     Rubbing in the pendulum wires  \
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_715e] ####         Effects:
%[text]             The overall effect of damping in an oscillator is to reduce the amplitude over time. However, is it possible that in a system with multiple independent modes, that each mode is effected by the damping a different amount, leading to a change in frequency?
%[text] 
%[text] To test this, lets look at a sligtly modified model where we'll add a damping term proportional to the velocity of each mass.
b= 0.05;

B = [ 0,          1,  0,          0;
      -k/m-g/r,  -b,  k/m,        0;
      0,          0,  0,          1;
      k/m,        0,  -k/m-g/r,  -b];

          %u1;  v1;     u2;  v2 
inits = [ 0.01;  0;  -0.01; 0 ];

[EigenVectors,EigenValues] = eig(B);

C = mldivide(EigenVectors , inits);

% order of operations matters!!!
A = EigenVectors * ( C .* exp( diag(EigenValues) .* (0:0.01:20) ) );

plot( (0:0.01:20), real(A([1,3],: )) ); %[output:9c6cf9ad]
